UAS INCIDENT: 2212 The Pilot of AAL1678departing RWY 27R reported a white UAS over RWY 27R moving S bound across the airport. ATL ATCT also observed the UAS flying across the Airport S bound towards the approach area for RWY 27L just as DAL2046 was on short-final to this Runway. ATL ATCT instructed DAL2046 tocancel itsapproach and go-around due to the close proximity of the UAS. ATL ATCT also observed a grey and black SUV parked on the access road on the S side of the Airport and an individual standing outside the vehicle who appeared to be controlling the UAS. The Individual quicklygot in his vehicle and left the areaafter the DAL2046 approach was disrupted. ATL Airport Operations was notified and they dispatched a vehicle to patrol the area with negative results. TSOC notified. MR notified.

DCA-1: Incident occurred at 1835 (1335L), first notification was made by Pentagon Police (Thomas Shannon) at 1925 (1425L). The Pentagon Police and Arlington PD received a report of a UAS being operated at 675 N Randolph Street, Arlington, VA. (approximately DCA300003.5). According to reports, the UAS was not being operated above the height of the building (unknown height / floors). It was also initially reported that they had received approval for the operation from the FAA. TSA NCRCC, FAA NCRCC and DCA ATCT were unable to locate any information on the operation. When Arlington PD arrived at the scene (1835Z /1335L),the UAS was flying and they ordered it down and the pilot complied immediately. They estimate that it had been flying for approximately 5 minutes. When FAANCRCC queried them reference having FAA approval, they replied that was not the case as the operator landed the aircraft immediately. POC for the Arlington PD: Lt Dan Murphy,. UAS Operator: Edgar Romero, Washington Digital Media, who stated that he was working for the construction company who was erecting a pedestrian walkway for the owners of the building. MOR completed by DCA. MX notified.

The pilot of ASH6022 originally reported a bird strike at approximately the DCA315020, which is N of Sterling, VA just W of the Trump National Golf course.   The aircraft was heading S at altitude 2,700 feet setting up for a landing on runway 19L.  No injuries or damage to aircraft were reported.  The strike occurred about 0025 Zulu and aircraft landed 0029 Zulu without incident.  The pilot reported a bird strike, but upon inspection of the aircraft on the ground, the crew could not locate any normal signs of a bird strike, such as blood, feathers or anything biological.  The crew upon reflection said the strike did not sound like a bird which is usually a soft thud, but it sounded more like a sharp crack like a baseball bat.   Because of the lack of biological evidence and the sharp sound of impact, the crew believes they hit a UAS.  Fairfax County PD is being notified of this incident.  0154:  The Washington Operations Center (WOC) called the FAA DEN position and told them Mesa Airlines (ASH) had a maintenance crew re examine the aircraft and the airline is now changing this incident to Bird Strike.  The airline did not pass to the FAA why they changed this report.  NFA.

MIA TRACON called to report that security for Turkey Point Nuclear Power Plant had called them to report UAS activity over the facility. Turkey Point Power Plant is located 4 NM SE of HST. HQ DEN took the name and number of the Security Company that works security for the plant. 0058 HQ DEN contacted Turkey Point Security. The Security Officer reported that they had 3 drones operating over the facility for roughly 50 minutes (1905-1950). The drones have since moved on, 2 went E over the water and one went W. Turkey Point Security disclosed they contacted HST and MIA to try to verify if the Facilities were aware of any approved drone operations with negative results. They also called the USCG to see if they could assist with the drones over the water. The drones were 3x3 ft with flashing red and white lights. HQ DEN checked with SOSC and confirmed there were no approved UAS operations in that area. HQ DEN then recommended Turkey Point Security contact Miami Dade 305-5985-6263 and report the drones and request their assistance in locating the operators of the UAS. At 0155 ATCT observed a UAS fly over the field, W bound at 400-500 feet, 1 NM W of GSO Airport. Airport Operations notified at. 0155 GSO ATCT reports to HQ DEN Airport Police are sweeping perimeter, UAS is still visible over departure corridor. ATCT is holding 2 IFR departures on RWY 23L due to proximity of UAS. 0210 UPDATE: GSO ATCT advised they utilized Opposite Direction Operations to depart RWY 05R with LBQ782 and VTM061. Arrivals will be utilizing RWY 23L. Local Police and Fire Department are continuing to sweep airport and perimeter for operator. 0238 UPDATE: GSO ATCT reports last sighting approximately 0230, UAS was N of the airport flying E/W lines. Operations returning to normal configuration, arriving and departing RWY 23L. GSO ATCT will file MOR. 0250 UPDATE: GSO ATCT observed the large UAS transition over the airport W to E, turning S at approximately 600 feet. UAS impacting airfield operations. Air Traffic Manager has directed ATCT to suspend operations UFN. Airfield Operations, Local Police and Fire Department continue to sweep airfield and perimeter for operator. 4 IFR arrivals potentially impacted for the 0400 hour, ZTL will track and report diversions and/or delays. 0335 UPDATE: NOTAM GSO 02/174 issued for UAS activity. AWO reports COVID-19 Vaccine Flight, FDX1041, is delaying departure at ORD due to UAS ongoing event. 0430 UPDATE: 0406 GSO ATCT reports UAS sighting by Airport Operations 1/2 NM N of Airport, N bound heading towards HWY 73. 0415 GSO ATCT reports UAS sighting by Airport Operations NE of the Airport on the extended centerline RWY 23L. Approximately 0400 ATCSCC has issued a Ground Stop for Air Traffic into GSO. ATCSCC reports 1 aircraft diversion, 7 aircraft in airborne holding, 7 aircraft captured in the Ground Stop as of 0430. FDX Operations still holding COVID-19 Vaccine flight on the ground in ORD to minimize risk of airborne holding or diversion. 0435 UPDATE: AMOC has been monitoring GSO UAS event and has observed no radar returns. GSO ATCT reports they have had no radar returns from UAS activity, however visual sightings reported by the ATCT, LEO and Airfield Operations. 0435 UPDATE: GSO Airfield Operations reports last verified/confirmed sighting was approximately 0300, UAS had steady green, flashing red lights and made no noise. Subsequent reports of UAS are unconfirmed by Airport Operations. 3 LEO Agencies are now involved in securing the airport perimeter and monitoring operations. 0440 CLOSEOUT: GSO ATCT reports to the ATCSCC they are now going to start accepting arrivals and departures, last sighting N of the airport. ATCSCC has notified FDX and stakeholders. AWO, JH, CT notified.

SUMMARY.CEDAR: On Wednesday, July 21, 2021 US Supreme Court reported to US Capitol Police (USCP) Headquarters that a UAS Drone was reported flying in the area of First and Maryland Avenue, NE, Washington, DC and crashed into the northside of the Supreme Court Building.  Officers from US Supreme Court, US Capitol Police, USCP Crime Scene, and USCP JTTF arrived on scene to investigate.  A red drone was found in the bushes and an investigation to locate the operator of the drone was met with negative results.   US Capitol Police did not have any camera footage of the drone.  The investigation was completed and the US Supreme court returned to normal operations at 1430.  The reported UAS's closest range to DCA was 2 nautical miles.  No further action was taken.

SUMMARY.CEDAR: AT APPROXIMATELY 0637Z ADW'S UAS COUNTERMEASURE SENSORS WERE ALERETED TO AN UNAUTHORIZED UAS OPERATING WITHIN THE BASE PERIMETER. THE ON-SCENE OFFICER INFORMED TOWER, VIA TELEPHONE, OF THE ACTIVITY, BUT WAS UNABLE TO PROVIDE ANY INFORMATION AS TO SIZE, TYPE, OR ALTITUDE, EXCEPT THAT THE INTRUDER HAD RED, GREEN, AND WHITE LIGHTS AND WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND. THE UAS WAS ORIGINALLY SPOTED NEAR THE PEARL HARBOR GATE WHICH IS LOCATED NEAR THE SOUTHEAST CORNER OF THE AIRFIELD. VISUAL CONFIRMATION WITH THE UAS LIGHTS WAS REPORTED LOST AT APPROX 0715Z. AN ADDITIONAL SIGHTING WAS MADE AT APPROXIMATLY 0737Z OVER THE AIR FORCE ONE HANGER 19.  THIS SIGHTING WAS CONFRIMED BY ADW SECURITY FORCES. THE VERBAL REPORTS RELAYED TO TOWER MENTIONED RED, GREEN, AND WHITE LIGHT. NO PERCISE DISCRIPTION WAS EVER OBSERVED, EXCEPT THE COLOR OF ITS LIGHTS. THE UAS DISSAPPEARED FROM LAW ENFORCEMENTS VIEW AND NO DIRECT ACTION WAS TAKEN AGAINST THE INTRUDER. ADW ATC CONTROLLERS WERE NEVER ABLE TO VIUSALLY CONFIRM WITH LEO'S REPORTS OF UAS/UAP SIGHTINGS.
QAFINDINGS.CEDAR: Facility summary reviewed. At approximately 0637Z ADW UAS countermeasure sensors were alerted to an unauthorized UAS operating within the base perimeter. The on-scene officer informed ATCT, via telephone, of the activity, but was unable to provide any information as to size, type, or altitude, except that the intruder had red, green, and white lights and was traveling southbound. The UAS was originally spotted near the Pearl Harbor gate which is located near the southeast corner of the airfield. Visual confirmation with the UAS lights was reported lost at approximately 0715z. An additional sighting was made at approximately 0737z over the Air Force one hanger 19.  This sighting was confirmed by ADW security forces. The verbal reports relayed to tower mentioned red, green, and white lights. No precise description was ever observed, except the color of its lights. The UAS disappeared from law enforcements view and no direct action was taken against the intruder. ADW ATCT controllers were never able to visually confirm the UAS/UAP sightings. MOR closed.

SUMMARY.CEDAR: During periodic inspection of the RNAV-A at W31 we had to maneuver to avoid a small remote controlled aircraft. The aircraft was less than 3 feet in wingspan and appeared to be something that could be bought at a hobby shop. There is a house immediately off the departure end of RWY 02 and the aircraft was operating over the house. We were able to avoid the remote aircraft and continued the mission with no further incident. ZDC QC comments, this report was submitted to the Flight Safety Program from a deidentified safety submission 5 days after the event.
QAFINDINGS.CEDAR: Facility summary reviewed. N84 was conducting an evaluation of an RNAV-A approach for RWY 2 at W31 airport in ZDC airspace. The RNAV approach for RWY 2 has a Go-around procedure with an initial heading of 360 degrees after initial climb is established. There is a house off the departure end of the runway and N84 encountered a remote control airplane over that house. Evasive maneuvers were taken to avoid the R/C airplane but the flight proceeded normally afterwards. The pilot did not declare a NMAC. The aircraft wasn't receiving ATC services at the time. The report was summitted 5 days after the event. No authorities were notified. MOR closed.
